<BaseLayout title=\"About — Kamal Nadh Sunkara\">
  <Header />

  <main>
    <section class=\"intro\">
      <p class=\"kicker\">About</p>
      <h1>From Desktop Support to Cloud Platforms — a journey through every layer of infrastructure.</h1>
      <p class=\"lede\">
        Like many computer engineers, I didn’t start with a grand plan to build cloud platforms.
        My early career was simple and practical — like most people entering IT at the time, I was
        just trying to understand what was good in the market, learn those skills, apply for jobs,
        and find stability in the industry.
      </p>
      <p>
        There was no “platform engineering” or “cloud-native” mindset back then. It was about
        getting into the industry and moving step by step.
      </p>
    </section>

    <hr />

    <section>
      <h2>Starting at the ground level</h2>
      <p>
        I began my journey as a <strong>Desktop Support Engineer</strong>. At that stage,
        everything was hands-on and user-focused — fixing machines, solving day-to-day issues,
        and making sure people could actually work. It taught me patience and fundamentals:
        how systems behave in real environments, not just theory.
      </p>
      <p>
        From there, I moved into <strong>Server Support</strong>. That was my first step into
        infrastructure. Suddenly I wasn’t just dealing with endpoints — I was dealing with
        systems that powered entire teams. It was my introduction to scale, reliability, and
        the importance of keeping services running.
      </p>
    </section>

    <hr />

    <section>
      <h2>Entering the Microsoft enterprise world</h2>
      <p>
        As I progressed, I moved deeper into Microsoft enterprise technologies — tools that, at
        the time, were the backbone of large organisations but aren’t even widely talked about
        by newer generations today.
      </p>
      <p>I worked with platforms like:</p>
      <ul class=\"bullets compact\">
        <li><strong>Source Depot</strong></li>
        <li><strong>VSTF</strong> — Visual Studio Team Foundation Server</li>
      </ul>
      <p style=\"margin-top:1rem;\">And then into more operational enterprise systems:</p>
      <ul class=\"bullets compact\">
        <li><strong>SCVMM</strong> — System Center Virtual Machine Manager</li>
        <li><strong>SCOM</strong> — System Center Operations Manager</li>
        <li><strong>SCCM</strong> — System Center Configuration Manager</li>
      </ul>
      <p style=\"margin-top:1rem;\">
        Each of these added a new layer of understanding. I didn’t just learn tools — I learned
        how enterprises actually run at scale. Eventually I became a specialist in <strong>SCCM</strong>,
        which gave me deep exposure to endpoint management, automation and large-scale system
        administration.
      </p>
    </section>

    <hr />

    <section>
      <h2>The shift to virtualization</h2>
      <p>
        From there, the next major shift came with <strong>VMware</strong>. This is where
        things started to feel different. Using my experience with SCVMM, I naturally
        transitioned into virtualization environments, and this was the first time I heard the
        term that would later define my career direction:
      </p>
      <blockquote>“Private Cloud”</blockquote>
      <p>
        At that time it wasn’t called cloud in the way we understand it today. It was
        virtualization, resource pooling and infrastructure abstraction — but the idea was
        forming. We were essentially building early versions of what would later become modern
        cloud platforms.
      </p>
      <p>
        That was the moment I started seeing the bigger picture. Infrastructure was no longer
        just servers and systems — it was becoming a <em>platform</em>.
      </p>
    </section>

    <hr />

    <section>
      <h2>Where it led me — from cloud to AI</h2>
      <p>
        Over time, my journey moved from infrastructure and cloud into something much broader:
        automation, intelligence, and now AI.
      </p>
      <p>
        As engineers, we often have ideas to improve how we work — automations, frameworks,
        tools that could make daily operations faster, smarter, and more efficient. But in
        reality, not every idea can be implemented.
      </p>
      <p>
        In most corporate environments, priorities are driven by company goals, budgets,
        policies and operational constraints. Even good ideas often stay as ideas because they
        require investment, dedicated teams, and long-term focus. And in today’s corporate
        world, with increasing pressure on cost optimisation, even strong innovation proposals
        can be difficult to push through.
      </p>
      <p>
        Unlike startups, where experimentation is part of the DNA, large enterprises tend to
        move with caution. At the same time, I’ve also realised I’m firmly part of the
        corporate world — I’m not in a position to simply switch into a startup environment or
        build a company from scratch today. And that’s where things started to change again.
      </p>
    </section>

    <hr />

    <section>
      <h2>The role of AI in this shift</h2>
      <p>
        With the rise of AI, something interesting has happened. AI has started to become a way
        to take those “unimplemented ideas” and actually shape them into working frameworks.
        What used to stay in my mind as architecture sketches or automation concepts can now be
        rapidly prototyped, structured and refined.
      </p>
      <p>
        AI is not just a tool anymore — it’s becoming a way to <strong>frame ideas, test
        architectures, and accelerate implementation</strong>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Yes, there is a real discussion about AI impacting jobs and changing the nature of
        work. That concern is valid and cannot be ignored. But from my perspective, the bigger
        shift is this:
      </p>
      <blockquote>
        If you understand how to use AI effectively — if you can combine it with your domain
        knowledge, your architecture thinking and your real-world engineering experience — you
        can turn ideas into systems faster than ever before.
      </blockquote>
    </section>

    <hr />

    <section>
      <h2>My perspective</h2>
      <p>
        I’m not trying to argue a point or predict the future with certainty. This is simply my
        personal perspective based on what I’ve seen over the years.
      </p>
      <p>
        Technology has always evolved in a way where new tools replace old limitations. Right
        now, AI feels like that next layer — not replacing thinking, but amplifying it. And
        for someone who has spent two decades building systems across every layer of
        infrastructure, it feels like the next natural extension of everything I’ve learned so
        far.
      </p>
    </section>

    <hr />

    <section>
      <h2>The journey, at a glance</h2>
      <ol class=\"timeline\">
        {chapters.map((c, i) => (
          <li>
            <span class=\"step\">{String(i + 1).padStart(2, '0')}</span>
            <div>
              <h3>{c.era} · {c.role}</h3>
              <p>{c.note}</p>
            </div>
          </li>
        ))}
      </ol>
    </section>

    <hr />

    <section class=\"two-col\">
      <div>
        <h2>Certifications</h2>
        <ul class=\"bullets\">{certs.map(c => <li>{c}</li>)}</ul>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h2>Education</h2>
        <ul class=\"bullets\">
          <li><strong>MSc Computer Science</strong> — Nagarjuna University (2003)</li>
          <li><strong>BSc Computer Science</strong> — Nagarjuna University (2001)</li>
        </ul>
        <h2 style=\"margin-top:1.5rem;\">Languages</h2>
        <ul class=\"bullets\">
          <li>English — fluent</li>
          <li>Hindi · Telugu — native</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <hr />

    <section class=\"contact\">
      <h2>Get in touch</h2>
      <p>
        I write here about cloud platforms, FinOps and the messy reality of multi-cloud — and
        increasingly about how AI is changing the way platform engineers work. If anything in
        this story resonated, I’d love to hear from you.
      </p>
      <div class=\"links\">
        <a href=\"https://www.linkedin.com/in/kamal-nadh-b1156b75/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">LinkedIn →</a>
        <a href=\"https://github.com/sunkarakamal\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">GitHub →</a>
        <a href=\"mailto:kamsun.uk@gmail.com\">Email →</a>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>

  <Footer />
</BaseLayout>

<style>
